title: For Sale/Trade:  Interdynamic KG-9 open bolt 9mm
location: St Louis area, Southern Illinois, Illinois
postcontent:
Up for trade is a used Interdynamic KG-9 semi automatic 9mm, serial #0316X. It shows handling marks on the top, and the rear sling attachment is missing. Included are 7 magazines (5 are still NIB, marked "003-9-001 KG-9 magazine 32/36 round") and an assault systems brand case. I don't know if the magazines are factory or aftermarket.

This is the gun that the ATF designated as a machine gun, but did not apply the ruling to those already manufactured, effectively "grandfathering" them.

Only 2500 of these were made before the company was forced to cease production in 1982 due to the gun being too easily converted to full auto. Of those 2500, some were legally converted to FA and registered before a 1986 deadline, some were illegally converted and subsequently confiscated and destroyed, and some were confiscated with missing serial numbers (due to the ease of removing the number from the plastic receiver) and destroyed. This puts the number of remaining KG-9s at less than 2500. A definite collectors item!

I'll consider cash offers, but looking more to trade. Thanks for looking!

For individuals out of state, it must ship to your local FFL. Please know the laws in your state.

title: For Sale:  WW II Quality Hardware M1 Carbine
location: NW Columbia (Irmo area), Columbia, South Carolina
postcontent:
Offered for sale is one of the first 50,000 M1 carbines built by Quality Hardware during WW II.  It is serial number 1595XXX and marked with the Quality name near the serial number.  Based on serial number records that I see on line, Quality built around one million carbines if all of the assigned serial numbers were actually used.  

The barrel is manufactured by Inland and the stock is marked with the Q-RMC in the sling/oiler cutout opening.  This carbine utilizes the low wood design stock front end and the oiler opening is oval cut.  The upper hand guard is the two rivet type and both are intact.  The metal finish is very good with no rust on the weapon and the stock has only very small dings with no major marking.  No rebuilt markings are visible on the stock. The barrel is clean with distinct lands and is very tight.  A field test (inserting 30 caliber carbine bullet into the end of the barrel) confirms the tight fit. 

The magazine release button has the M marking and the back of the operating slide has a number 4 imprinted on it as well as D-7161843-7 HSA on the bottom of the assembly.  The original push button safety has been retained.  The adjustable rear sight and bayonet mount likely were added at a later date but I have no way of confirming that educated assumption.  

This carbine appears to be a very nice weapon that could be considered collector grade.   A correct GI sling/oiler is included with the carbine but no magazines.  An original GI magazine can be purchased separately if needed.  

This is one of the nicest WW II carbines that I have see and is priced reasonably for what you are getting.  It has no visible import marks and likely remained in US service until removed from the government inventory.  High resolution internal and external photos of this weapon are available on request.  Shipping (if required) will be at the expense of the purchaser.

title: For Sale:  Bushmaster 14.5 pinned M4 build
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Bushmaster M4gery build. This started life as a stock rifle. I ended up swapping out the original upper assembly, bolt, buffer tube and stock. I originally was planning to put together an M4 SOPMOD Block 1.5/ Phased Replacement rifle inspired by pics of SEALs and SF boys overseas. 
The barrel is a Bushmaster 1/7 chromed lined gov't profile barrel (unfortunately the front sight is not F marked) that was purchased through PKfirearms a few years back. The flash hider was pinned locally and left with the spot weld in place in order to minimize any ATF headaches should they ever occur. The upper reciever is a YHM with m4 feedramps to match the ones in the barrel extension. The Bolt is made by LMT. Semi Auto Bolt Carrier and small parts are the original Bushmaster parts that I held onto. The stock tube was replaced by a mil-spec tube and fitted with an M4 waffle stock from LMT (nice and tight fit for a USGI style stock); steel sling loop removed but I will include it with the rifle; buffer and spring are original. I have fitted a well-worn KAC M4 RAS onto the rifle in lieu of the old plastic handuards; no rail covers included. The entire rifle was painted in desert colors that have since worn out on all the edges from exposure to solvents and CLP. 
Accessories include: 
-Surefire G2 incandescent in black on VTAC mount in coyote tan 
-KAC VFG 
-Matech BUIS 
-VTAC padded sling in coyote (I had it mounted on the rifle with the intention of putting a QD socket on the stock and looped some 550 cord through the front ala Frank Proctor's slings. 
-USGI 30rd magazine with magpul follower. 

This was just waiting on an EOTech 553 to round out the SOPMOD PR/Block 1.5 setup. Or one could throw on an ACOG/ M68 for a classic Block 1 look. 

I have put about 4000 rounds through the gun over the past 3 years (a very limited firing schedule, no crazy magdumps, only two low round-count classes/clinics) with this upper/barrel/bolt combo with no hiccups. 
Asking 1000 even FTF in Las Vegas, NV area.

title: For Sale:  Desert Eagle
postcontent: The Desert Eagle is a large-caliber handgun, commonly chambered for .357 Magnum, .44 Magnum, or .50 Action Express. The American company Magnum Research designed and patented the Desert Eagle with assistance by Israeli Military Industries (now known as Israeli Weapon Industries) during the late 70s and early 80s. During much of it's existence, it was manufactured chiefly in Israel by Israeli Weapon Industries. In June of 2010, Magnum Research was purchased by Kahr Arms, who decided to bring the Desert Eagle's manufacture to Minnesota. The Desert Eagle contains a gas-operated mechanism characteristic of automatic rifles as opposed to the usual mechanisms (direct or delayed blowback) found in other semi-automatic pistols.
